         <div type="edition" xml:lang="grc" xml:space="preserve">

<ab><lb n="1"/><gap reason="lost" unit="character" quantity="1"/>  <persName type="attested"><name nymRef="#Οὐλπία"><unclear reason="damage">Οὐλπ</unclear><supplied reason="lost">ία</supplied></name>  <name nymRef="#Ἀπολλώνιος"><supplied reason="lost">Ἀπο</supplied><lb n="2" break="no"/><supplied reason="lost">λ</supplied>λωνίου</name> <w><unclear reason="damage">πρε</unclear><supplied reason="lost">ιμο</supplied><lb n="3" break="no"/>      πειλαρίου</w>  <w lemma="καί">καὶ</w><lb n="4"/> <w lemma="ἀπό">ἀπὸ</w> <w>στρατο<lb n="5" break="no"/>πεδαρχίας</w><lb n="6"/> <w>θυγατὴρ</w> <name nymRef="#Ἀπολλωνία">Ἀπολ<lb n="7" break="no"/>      λωνία</name></persName> <w lemma="ὁ">τῇ</w> <w>Πα<lb n="8" break="no"/>      <g ref="#scroll"/>  τρίδι</w>  <g ref="#leaf"/></ab>
</div>
         <div type="translation">
            <p>Ulpia Apollonia, daughter of Apollonius, <term xml:lang="la">primipilarius</term>, and former camp prefect, to her homeland.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="commentary">
            <p>One of the series of dedications from the East Court of the Hadrianic Baths: <ref type="iAph" target="">1184</ref>, <ref type="iAph" target="">1186</ref>, <ref type="iAph" target="">1187</ref>, <ref type="iAph" target="">1188</ref>, <ref type="iAph" target="">1189</ref>, <ref type="iAph" target="">1190</ref>, <ref type="iAph" target="">1191</ref>, <ref type="iAph" target="">1192</ref>, <ref type="iAph" target="">1193</ref>, <ref type="iAph" target="">1194</ref>, <ref type="iAph" target="">1195</ref>, <ref type="iAph" target="">1196</ref>, <ref type="iAph" target="">1197</ref>, <ref type="iAph" target="">1198</ref>, <ref type="iAph" target="">1200</ref>, <ref type="iAph" target="">1201</ref>, <ref type="iAph" target="">1202</ref>, <ref type="iAph" target="">1203</ref>, <ref type="iAph" target="">1204</ref>, <ref type="iAph" target="">1205</ref>, <ref type="iAph" target="">1206</ref>, <ref type="iAph" target="">1207</ref>, <ref type="iAph" target="">1208</ref>, <ref type="iAph" target="">1209</ref>, <ref type="iAph" target="">1210</ref> ; all are by women, and apparently bore caryatids (see <ref type="iAph" target="">1198</ref>).</p>
            <p>
               <ref type="iAph" target="">1200</ref> (=84.55) is the same text, but with a different layout.</p>
         </div>
         <div type="bibliography" n="none">
            <p>Unpublished.</p>
         </div>
